## PROJECT OVERVIEW

This is a single-page, vanilla HTML/CSS/JS baseball puzzle game. Players count down from 1000 to exactly 0 using MLB players' career home run totals. It runs entirely in the browser with no build step, no framework, and no backend.

---

## REPO STRUCTURE

```
/
├── index.html                        # ← ENTIRE GAME lives here (HTML + CSS + JS)
├── players.json                      # ← Player database (source of truth for all HR data)
├── README.md                         # ← Setup and deployment docs
├── scripts/
│   └── update_stats.py               # ← Nightly MLB API updater (Python)
└── .github/
    └── workflows/
        └── update-players.yml        # ← GitHub Action: runs update_stats.py on schedule
```

**Critical rule:** The entire game is ONE FILE — `index.html`. Do not split it into separate JS or CSS files unless explicitly asked. All styles go in `<style>`, all logic goes in `<script>`, at the bottom of index.html.

---

## TECH STACK & CONSTRAINTS

- **No frameworks.** Vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript only.
- **No npm, no build tools, no bundlers.** The game must work by opening index.html directly in a browser.
- **No localStorage or sessionStorage.** All state is managed in memory via JavaScript variables.
- **No external JS libraries** unless loaded from a CDN via a `<script src>` tag (and only if truly necessary).
- **CSS custom properties** (variables) are used for all colors and spacing — always use the existing `--variable` names rather than hardcoding values.
- **Google Fonts** are loaded via a `<link>` in the `<head>`. Do not change the fonts (Bebas Neue, DM Serif Display, DM Mono, Inter) without being asked.
- **GitHub Pages** hosting — everything must work as static files, no server-side logic.

