## PLAYERS.JSON SCHEMA

Each player entry follows this exact schema. Never add or remove fields without updating the nightly update script too.

```json
{
  "name": "Player Name",        // string — full name, used as unique ID
  "hr": 123,                    // integer — career home run total
  "positions": ["CF", "RF"],    // array of strings — all positions played
  "teams": ["NYY", "BOS"],      // array of strings — all teams (3-letter MLB codes)
  "active": false               // boolean — true if currently active MLB player
}
```

### Valid position codes
`C`, `1B`, `2B`, `3B`, `SS`, `LF`, `CF`, `RF`, `DH`, `SP`, `RP`

### Valid team codes (MLB 3-letter abbreviations)
`ARI`, `ATL`, `BAL`, `BOS`, `CHC`, `CWS`, `CIN`, `CLE`, `COL`, `DET`,
`HOU`, `KC`, `LAA`, `LAD`, `MIA`, `MIL`, `MIN`, `NYM`, `NYY`, `OAK`,
`PHI`, `PIT`, `SD`, `SF`, `SEA`, `STL`, `TB`, `TEX`, `TOR`, `WAS`,
`MON`, `FLA`, `CAL`, `ANA`, `BKN`, `NYG`, `WAS` (historical codes are also valid)

### Rules for editing players.json
- Player `"name"` is the unique identifier — the game uses it to prevent duplicates. Never change a name without a find-and-replace throughout the codebase.
- Always keep the array sorted with active players last (retired players first by convention) — or don't sort at all, the game handles filtering dynamically.
- `"active": true` players will have their `"hr"` value overwritten nightly by the GitHub Action. Don't manually set HR for active players expecting it to stay — use the action.

